Remarks. The present material agrees well with the diagnosis of the species given by
Chan ( 1996 )
.
Pontocaris pennata
is a very common crangonid species in the East and South China Seas from the coastal waters of mainland China . The material examined was mainly collected by the National Comprehensive Oceanography Survey and the China-Vietnam Comprehensive Oceanographic Survey to Beibu Gulf in all months except for June and September in
1959–1960
and 1962 . The number ratio of males, non-ovigerous females and ovigerous females was 54 : 77 : 17 in January, 56 : 84 : 76 in April, 26 : 76 : 26 in July and 63 : 89 : 8 in October (
Fig. 1
). The absolute and relative numbers of the ovigerous females were highest in April, lowest in October and November. It is suggested that the species bred in all seasons of a year, the peak of breeding was in April.

The average carapace lengths of the males, non-ovigerous females and ovigerous females are shown in
Figure 2
. With regard to the average carapace lengths, the males appeared generally smaller than the nonovigerous females, and the non-ovigerous females were smaller than the ovigerous females, with an exception in December in which the average carapace length of the non-ovigerous females was larger than that of the ovigerous females. The smallest male appeared in April with the carapace length was 5.1 mm , the largest male appeared in January with the carapace length was 9.2 mm . The largest non-ovigerous female was collected in July with the carapace length of 11.0 mm. The smallest ovigerous female appeared in January with the carapace length of 7.1 mm , the largest appeared in October with the carapace length was 11.0 mm. The largest average carapace length of the males occurred in May and the smallest in August; the largest average carapace length of the non-ovigerous females occurred in April and the smallest in August; the largest average carapace length of the ovigerous females occurred in March and the smallest in December.

Based on the collection data, we found that more than 80 % individuals occured at the depths of 40–100 meters, about 50 % occured at the depths of 60–89.9 meters (
Fig. 3
). The distributions of the species in different seasons are illustrated in
Figure 4
. In April (Spring), the population had the highest density, consistent with the population numbers of
Figure 1
.

Pontocaris penata
)
and
Liu & Zhong ( 1994 )
, from the South China Sea by
Chan ( 1996 )
.
